items.name: Ext.form.trigger.Component
items.text: A Text Field Trigger that contains a Ext.Component or Ext.Widget.

items.name: component
items.text:
A config object for a Component or Widget,
or an already instantiated Component or Widget.

items.name: extraCls
items.text:
An additional CSS class (or classes) to be added to the trigger's element. Can
be a single class name (e.g. 'foo') or a space-separated list of class names
(e.g. 'foo bar').

items.name: handler
items.text: Function to run when trigger is clicked or tapped.

items.name: hidden
items.text: `true` to initially render the trigger hidden.

items.name: hideOnReadOnly
items.text: Set 'false' to prevent trigger from being hidden even though the related field is set Ext.form.field.Text#readOnly

items.name: preventMouseDown
items.text:
If true, preventDefault() will be called on the mousedown event.  This prevents
a click on the trigger from blurring the field, which is desirable in most cases.
File field sets this to false, because preventing the default behavior of touchstart
prevents the browser's file dialog from opening.

items.name: repeatClick
items.text: `true` to attach a Ext.util.ClickRepeater to the trigger

items.name: scope
items.text: Execution context for the handler function.

items.name: weight
items.text:
An optional weighting to change the ordering of the items. The default weight is
`0`.  Triggers are sorted by weight in ascending order before being rendered.
The value may be a negative value in order to position custom triggers ahead of
default triggers like that of ComboBox.

items.name: width
items.text: The trigger's width, in pixels. Typically this is not needed as the trigger width is normally determined by the style sheet, (see Ext.form.field.Text#$form-trigger-width or Ext.form.field.Text#$extjs-text-field-ui).

items.name: afterFieldRender
items.text: Called when this trigger's field is rendered

items.name: constructor
items.text: Creates new Object.

items.name: value
items.text: The value to wrap.

items.name: getEl
items.text: Get the element for this trigger.
The element for this trigger, null if not rendered.

items.name: getStateEl
items.text: Returns the element that should receive the "state" classes - focusCls, overCls, and clickCls.

items.name: hasOwnProperty
prop
items.text: The name of the property to test.

Returns true if object contains specified property; else
returns false.

items.name: hide
items.text: Hides the trigger

items.name: isPrototypeOf
prototype
items.text:
an object to be tested against each link in the prototype chain of the
*object* argument

items.name: object
items.text: the object whose prototype chain will be searched
Returns true if object is a prototype and false if not.

items.name: isVisible
items.text: Returns `true` if this Trigger is visible.
`true` if this trigger is visible, `false` otherwise.

items.name: onClick
items.text: Handles a click on the trigger's element

items.name: onFieldBlur
items.text: Called when this trigger's field is blurred

items.name: onFieldFocus
items.text: Called when this trigger's field is focused

items.name: onFieldRender
items.text: Called when this trigger's field is rendered

items.name: propertyIsEnumerable
prop
items.text: The name of the property to test.

If the object does not have the specified property, this
method returns false.

items.name: renderBody
items.text: Renders the bodyTpl

items.name: renderTrigger
items.text:
Generates the trigger markup. Called during rendering of the field the trigger
belongs to.

items.name: fieldData
items.text: The render data object of the parent field.

items.name: show
items.text: Shows the trigger

items.name: toLocaleString
items.text: Returns a string representing the object. This method is meant to be overridden by derived objects for locale-specific purposes. Objects toLocaleString returns the result of calling toString. This function is provided to give objects a generic toLocaleString method, even though not all may use it. Currently, only Array, Number, and Date override toLocaleString.
Object represented as a string.

items.name: toString

items.text: Object represented as a string.

items.name: valueOf
items.text: Returns the primitive value of the specified object. JavaScript calls the valueOf method to convert an object to a primitive value. You rarely need to invoke the valueOf method yourself; JavaScript automatically invokes it when encountering an object where a primitive value is expected. By default, the valueOf method is inherited by every object descended from Object. Every built- in core object overrides this method to return an appropriate value. If an object has no primitive value, valueOf returns the object itself, which is displayed as: [object Object] You can use valueOf within your own code to convert a built-in object into a primitive value. When you create a custom object, you can override `Object.valueOf` to call a custom method instead of the default Object method. You can create a function to be called in place of the default valueOf method. Your function must take no arguments. Suppose you have an object type `myNumberType` and you want to create a valueOf method for it. The following code assigns a user-defined function to the object's valueOf method: myNumberType.prototype.valueOf = new Function(functionText) With the preceding code in place, any time an object of type `myNumberType` is used in a context where it is to be represented as a primitive value, JavaScript automatically calls the function defined in the preceding code. An object's valueOf method is usually invoked by JavaScript, but you can invoke it yourself as follows: myNumber.valueOf() Note: Objects in string contexts convert via the toString method, which is different from String objects converting to string primitives using valueOf. All objects have a string conversion, if only `"[object type]"`. But many objects do not convert to number, boolean, or function.
Returns value of the object or the object itself.

items.name: baseCls
items.text: The base CSS class that is always added to the trigger element.

items.name: bodyTpl
items.text: An optional template for rendering child elements inside the trigger element. Useful for creating more complex triggers such as Ext.form.trigger.Spinner.

items.name: clickCls
items.text: The CSS class that is added to the trigger element it is clicked.

items.name: component
items.text: The component or widget

items.name: constructor
el
items.text: The trigger's main element

items.name: factoryConfig
items.text: If this property is specified by the target class of this mixin its properties are used to configure the created Ext.Factory.

items.name: focusCls
items.text: The CSS class that is added to the trigger element when the field is focused.

items.name: getBodyRenderData
items.text: Allows addition of data to the render data object for the bodyTpl.

items.name: overCls
items.text: The CSS class that is added to the trigger element when it is hovered.

items.name: prototype
items.text: Allows the addition of properties to all objects of type Object.
